<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-III-6-sols">
        <title><m>\S III.6</m>: Counting and Cardinality </title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Motivation: Counting </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We've used "cardinality" to describe the number of elements in a set. This becomes less useful
                            when our sets are infinite. We introduce a better definition of cardinality, and will practice
                            using it to justify some common counting formulas.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Definition: Cardinality</title>
                    
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            The <term>cardinality of a finite set <m>A</m></term> is <m>n</m> if 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            there is a bijection between the elements of <m>A</m> and the set <m>\{1, 2, \dots , n\}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Example 1: Counting</title>
                    
                    
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            If <m>|A| = m</m> and <m>|B| = n</m>, then <m>|A \times B| = mn</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            This is justified by the bijection 
                            <me>
                                A \times B \to \{1,2,\dots, mn\}, (a_i,b_j) \mapsto (j-1)m + i
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Example 2: Counting</title>
                    
                    
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            If <m>|A| = n</m>, then <m>|P(A)| = 2^n</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            This is justified by the bijection
                            <me>
                                P(A) \to \{0,1\} \times \{0,1\} \times \cdots \times \{0,1\}, S \mapsto (\chi_S(a_1), \chi_S(a_2), \dots, \chi_S(a_n))
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Counting</title>
                    <introduction>
                        <p>
                            Justify the following statements, assuming <m>|A| = n</m> and <m>|B| = m</m>.
                        </p>
                    </introduction>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                The number of different relations between <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is <m>2^{nm}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                This is the number of elements in <m>P(A \times B)</m>. Using 
                                our previous result, <m>|P(A \times B)| = 2^{nm}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                The number of different functions from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> is <m>m^n</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                We can think of a function as and ordered <m>n</m>-tuple, where the element in 
                                coordinate <m>i</m> is <m>f(a_i)</m>. Since there are <m>m</m> choices for each of the 
                                <m>n</m> coordinates, this gives us <m>m^n</m> different functions.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                The number of different injective functions from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> is 
                                <m>m(m-1)(m-2) \cdots (m-n+1)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                This is similar to the above, except now we cannot repeat elements, and we must also have 
                                <m>m \ geq n</m> for this to be non-zero. This gives <m>m(m-1)(m-2) \cdots (m-n+1) = \frac{m!}{(m-n)!}</m>
                                different injective functions.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                The number of different bijective functions from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> is <m>n!</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                To be a bijection, we must have <m>m=n</m>. Using the previous formula, this gives <m>n!</m>
                                different bijections.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Counting</title>
                    <introduction>
                        <p>
                            Suppose a license plate has <m>4</m> capital letters followed by <m>2</m> digits. For example, 
                            ABCD12 is a valid license plate.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We can imagine a license plate combination being chosen by functions:
                            <me>
                                f: \{1,2,3,4\} \to \{A,B, C, \dots, Z\}
                            </me>
                            and
                            <me>
                                g: \{1,2\} \to \{0,1,2, \dots, 9\}
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </introduction>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                How many different license plate combinations are there?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>26^4\cdot 10^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                How does your answer change if no letters can be repeated?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>26 \cdot 25 \cdot 24 \cdot 23 \cdot 10^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                How does your answer change if no digits can be repeated?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>26^4\cdot 10 \cdot 9</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                How does your answer change if no letters or digits can be repeated?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>26 \cdot 25 \cdot 24 \cdot 23 \cdot 10 \cdot 9</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

        </worksheet>
    </article>
